          textEn: [
            "Inscription for My Humble Room \u2014 Liu Yuxi",
            "A mountain need not be high; with an immortal, it becomes famous. Water need not be deep; with a dragon, it becomes sacred. This is a humble room, but my virtue makes it fragrant. Moss grows green on the steps; grass appears blue through the curtain. Chatting and laughing with learned scholars; no common folk come and go. One may play the simple lute, read the golden scriptures. No noisy music to disturb the ears, no government documents to tire the body. Like Zhuge Liang\u2019s hut in Nanyang, Zi Yun\u2019s pavilion in Western Shu. Confucius said: \u2018What is humble about it?\u2019",
            "On the Love of the Lotus \u2014 Zhou Dunyi",
            "Of flowers on land and water, many are lovable. I alone love the lotus: rising from mud yet unstained, washed by clear ripples yet not seductive, hollow within and straight without, neither creeping nor branching, its fragrance growing purer at a distance, standing gracefully upright\u2014to be admired from afar, not to be trifled with.",
            "I say the chrysanthemum is the hermit of flowers; the peony, the aristocrat; the lotus, the gentleman."
          ],
